{"id":"2112.13632","submitter":"Michael Sachs","authors":"Erin E Gabriel and Michael C Sachs and Arvid Sj\\\"olander","title":"Sharp nonparametric bounds for decomposition effects with two binary\n  mediators","comments":null,"journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"stat.ME","license":"http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/4.0/","abstract":"  In randomized trials, once the total effect of the intervention has been\nestimated, it is often of interest to explore mechanistic effects through\nmediators along the causal pathway between the randomized treatment and the\noutcome. In the setting with two sequential mediators, there are a variety of\ndecompositions of the total risk difference into mediation effects. We derive\nsharp and valid bounds for a number of mediation effects in the setting of two\nsequential mediators both with unmeasured confounding with the outcome. We\nprovide five such bounds in the main text corresponding to two different\ndecompositions of the total effect, as well as the controlled direct effect,\nwith an additional thirty novel bounds provided in the supplementary materials\ncorresponding to the terms of twenty-four four-way decompositions. We also show\nthat, although it may seem that one can produce sharp bounds by adding or\nsubtracting the limits of the sharp bounds for terms in a decomposition, this\nalmost always produces valid, but not sharp bounds that can even be completely\nnoninformative. We investigate the properties of the bounds by simulating\nrandom probability distributions under our causal model and illustrate how they\nare interpreted in a real data example.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Mon, 27 Dec 2021 12:42:53 GMT"}],"update_date":"2021-12-28"}
