{"id":"2112.13736","submitter":"Jorge Salas","authors":"Cristian Riveros, Jorge Salas and Oskar Skibski","title":"How do centrality measures choose the root of trees?","comments":null,"journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"cs.DB cs.DM cs.SI","license":"http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/4.0/","abstract":"  Centrality measures are widely used to assign importance to graph-structured\ndata. Recently, understanding the principles of such measures has attracted a\nlot of attention. Given that measures are diverse, this research has usually\nfocused on classes of centrality measures. In this work, we provide a different\napproach by focusing on classes of graphs instead of classes of measures to\nunderstand the underlying principles among various measures. More precisely, we\nstudy the class of trees. We observe that even in \\fix{the} case of trees,\nthere is no consensus on which node should be selected as the most central. To\nanalyze the behavior of centrality measures on trees, we introduce a property\nof \\emph{tree rooting} that states a measure selects one or two adjacent nodes\nas the most important, and the importance decreases from them in all\ndirections. This property is satisfied by closeness centrality but violated by\nPageRank. We show that, for several centrality measures that root trees, the\ncomparison of adjacent nodes can be inferred by \\emph{potential functions} that\nassess the quality of trees. We use these functions to give fundamental\ninsights on rooting and derive a characterization explaining why some measure\nroot trees. Moreover, we provide an almost liner-time algorithm to compute the\nroot of a graph by using potential functions. Finally, using a family of\npotential functions, we show that many ways of tree rooting exist with\ndesirable properties.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Mon, 27 Dec 2021 15:36:48 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Tue, 28 Dec 2021 19:38:13 GMT"},{"version":"v3","created":"Tue, 